  "prompt": "Can a constitutional amendment be deemed unconstitutional by the Supreme Court?",
  "response": "No, a constitutional amendment cannot be deemed unconstitutional by the Supreme Court because it is part of the Constitution itself, which is the supreme law of the land. When an amendment is properly ratified according to the procedures outlined in Article V of the Constitution, it becomes an integral part of the Constitution. The Supreme Court's role is to interpret the Constitution, including all its amendments, rather than to evaluate the Constitution's validity.",
